# Fluff Date: 2026-02-28 17:47:08
overview:<p>The Gunslinger is an eighty-five-ton assault BattleMech introduced in 3053 as a joint Draconis Combine-Federated Commonwealth project born from the Clan Invasion. Designed while engineers from both states were assisting the Free Rasalhague Republic against the Clan onslaught, the Gunslinger was intended to bring Inner Sphere firepower capable of matching Clan weapons at long range. Produced by Defiance Industries on Hesperus II and Independence Weaponry on Quentin, the design quickly proved its worth in the desperate battles of the late Clan Invasion era. The Gunslinger's dual-Gauss configuration filled a critical gap in Inner Sphere assault doctrine, providing a platform that could trade effective fire with Clan opponents at distances previously dominated by OmniMech technology, earning a reputation as one of the most reliable heavy-hitting platforms of its generation.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Gunslinger's design philosophy centers on its twin arm-mounted Poland Main Model A Gauss rifles, weapons capable of stripping a full ton of armor at ranges exceeding six hundred meters. This devastating long-range punch is supported by a secondary weapons array reminiscent of the venerable BattleMaster, four Defiance B3M medium lasers distributed across the torsos provide credible close-range firepower, while a Defiance A5L small laser supplements them at point-blank range. Two rear-mounted Defiance P5M medium pulse lasers protect against flanking attacks, a configuration acknowledging the 'Mech's limited mobility.</p><p>A VOX 255 XL engine gives the Gunslinger a top speed of only fifty-four kilometers per hour, but a pair of HildCo Model 12 jump jets allow it to clear obstacles and gain advantageous firing positions. Where the design truly distinguishes itself is in its electronic warfare suite, a Guardian ECM system and Beagle Active Probe provide detection capabilities and electronic countermeasures unusual for an assault platform. Nearly maximum armor coverage with Kevlar 5000 plating ensures the 'Mech can withstand the return fire its prominent silhouette inevitably attracts, though the XL engine remains a critical vulnerability if either side torso is breached.</p>

deployment:<p>Introduced around 3062, this variant retains the proven twin Gauss rifle and Guardian ECM configuration while upgrading the four standard medium lasers to extended-range models, substantially improving the variant's effectiveness at intermediate distances. The Beagle Active Probe, rear-mounted medium pulse lasers, and small laser were removed to accommodate a C3 master computer and a third jump jet, increasing the 'Mech's jump capacity to ninety meters. This refocused the design from an independent electronic warfare platform to a network-centric command unit capable of sharing targeting data across an entire lance while maintaining improved tactical mobility.</p>

history:<p>The Gunslinger's development is inseparable from the political upheaval of the Clan Invasion. Born from the unlikely cooperation between the Draconis Combine and Federated Commonwealth (bitter rivals who set aside decades of mutual animosity to face the Clan threat) the design stands as perhaps the most tangible result of their wartime alliance. Engineers from both states collaborated while assisting the beleaguered Free Rasalhague Republic, and the resulting 'Mech reflected their shared need for a heavy platform capable of trading blows with Clan opponents at range.</p><p>The first Gunslinger walked off Defiance Industries' production line on Hesperus II on December 5, 3053, though it would be nearly two more years before Independence Weaponry's Quentin facility produced its first unit. The delay at Quentin was attributed to persistent difficulties with the Poland Main Gauss rifle systems, a common problem given the weapon's complexity. Once both production lines were running, demand consistently outstripped supply as both states recognized the value of a dual-Gauss assault platform.</p><p>The Gunslinger proved its combat effectiveness during Operation Guerrero in 3057 and the Jade Falcon incursion into the Lyran Alliance in 3058. During Operation Bulldog, the design cemented its reputation when the Seventh Sword of Light deployed two full lances of Gunslingers against the Smoke Jaguars' Third Assault Cluster. Positioned ahead of the retreating Clan force, the Gunslingers caught the Jaguar warriors in a devastating crossfire that destroyed more than a dozen OmniMechs, though only two of the Gunslingers survived the engagement, the battle cemented the 'Mech's fearsome reputation.</p><p>The Jihad era brought upheaval to the Gunslinger's production network. Independence Weaponry on Quentin fell under Word of Blake control, while Defiance Industries on Hesperus II faced disruption under contested Lyran authority. Following the Jihad, the Quentin facility operated under Republic of the Sphere oversight before transitioning through a period of independence and ultimately returning to Draconis Combine control. Defiance Industries resumed normal Lyran operations, though Gunslinger production at Hesperus II has been intermittent since the Civil War era.</p><p>By the Dark Age, the Gunslinger remained a valued design across the Inner Sphere. The introduction of the GUN-3ERD in 3131 as a joint Lyran-Combine-Republic project echoed the original design's cooperative origins, though the Blackout and subsequent conflicts shattered this renewed partnership. Both the Lyran Commonwealth and Draconis Combine continued independent production, with the Gunslinger serving in prestige units such as the Davion Assault Guards, the First Royal Guards, the First Sword of Light, and various mercenary commands including the Kell Hounds.</p>

